  "text": "## Rust Edition 2018 to 2021 Import Path Migration Analysis\n\n### Edition-Specific Prelude Module Exports\n\nThe prelude system in Rust implements edition-specific exports that differ between Edition 2015, 2018, 2021, and 2024:\n\n**std/library/std/src/prelude/mod.rs** defines the standard library prelude with edition-specific modules:\n- `rust_2015` and `rust_2018`: Re-export `v1` prelude (lines 120-134)\n- `rust_2021`: Re-exports `v1` plus additional traits `TryFrom`, `TryInto`, and `FromIterator` from core prelude (lines 140-148)\n- `rust_2024`: Adds `Future` and `IntoFuture` from `std::future` (lines 154-162)\n\n**library/core/src/prelude/mod.rs** similarly defines core prelude with parallel edition-specific modules (lines 38-50, 56-72), where 2021+ editions include `FromIterator`, `TryFrom`, and `TryInto`.\n\nThe prelude v1 modules (`library/std/src/prelude/v1.rs` and `library/core/src/prelude/v1.rs`) contain the base prelude items that are common to all editions 2015 and later.\n\n### Standard Library Automatic Import Injection\n\n**compiler/rustc_builtin_macros/src/standard_library_imports.rs** is the critical file that implements automatic prelude injection. The `inject()` function (lines 11-78) handles edition-specific prelude path construction:\n\n- Line 42: For Edition 2018+, the import path uses `def_site_ctxt`; for 2015, it uses `call_site_ctxt`\n- Lines 54-61: Constructs edition-specific prelude paths:\n  - `Edition2015 => sym::rust_2015`\n  - `Edition2018 => sym::rust_2018`\n  - `Edition2021 => sym::rust_2021`\n  - `Edition2024 => sym::rust_2024`\n- Line 50: In 2015 edition, paths include `kw::PathRoot` for crate-relative resolution; 2018+ editions omit it\n- Line 46: Uses `macro_use` attribute for the extern crate declaration\n\n### Edition-Specific Panic Macro Handling\n\n**compiler/rustc_builtin_macros/src/edition_panic.rs** implements edition-specific panic macro expansion:\n\n- The `expand_panic()` function (lines 17-24) routes to either `panic_2015` or `panic_2021` macros based on edition\n- The `use_panic_2021()` function (lines 70-84) determines which panic macro variant to use by checking the edition at the expansion site, respecting `#[allow_internal_unstable(edition_panic)]`\n- Line 82: Returns `expn.edition >= Edition::Edition2021` to determine which variant to use\n\n**library/core/src/panic.rs** defines the actual macro variants:\n- `panic_2015` macro (lines 24-44): Includes message-only and formatted panic forms\n- `panic_2021` macro (lines 51-64): Simplified form that always uses format_args!, eliminating the separate `panic_str_2015` call\n\nThe difference: 2015 edition panic allows `panic!(expr)` for non-string expressions with a special `panic_str_2015` call; 2021 edition requires format_args for all multi-argument panics.\n\n### Resolver Behavior Changes for Import Path Resolution\n\n**compiler/rustc_resolve/src/lib.rs** defines the core path resolution types with edition differences:\n\nThe `ModuleOrUniformRoot` enum (lines 432-449) includes three variants that differ by edition:\n- `Module`: Regular module resolution\n- `ExternPrelude`: Used for paths starting with `::` in 2018+ editions (line 442-443)\n- `ModuleAndExternPrelude`: Virtual module used for paths starting with `::` from 2015 edition macros used in 2018+ edition crates (lines 437-439)\n\n**compiler/rustc_resolve/src/imports.rs** documents the edition-specific path resolution (lines 182-183):\n- `use ::foo` in 2018+ editions: `ModuleOrUniformRoot::ExternPrelude`\n- `use ::foo` in 2015 edition: `ModuleOrUniformRoot::ModuleAndExternPrelude` (special case)\n\n**compiler/rustc_resolve/src/ident.rs** implements the scope visiting logic with edition handling:\n\n- Line 115: Checks `ctxt.edition().is_rust_2015()` to determine scope behavior\n- Line 160: `MacroUsePrelude` scope is only visited in 2015 edition or when `use_prelude` is true\n- Lines 162-164: `ExternPreludeItems` and `ExternPreludeFlags` are visited differently based on edition context\n- Lines 202-208: When `ModuleAndExternPrelude` scope set is used (only in special 2015 edition cases), it transitions to `ExternPreludeItems` for TypeNS but breaks for ValueNS and MacroNS\n- Lines 1792-1799: Critical edition transition logic - when processing `::a::b` from a 2015 edition macro in a 2018+ edition crate, uses `ModuleAndExternPrelude` for fallback resolution\n\n**compiler/rustc_resolve/src/build_reduced_graph.rs** implements macro_use attribute handling:\n\n- `process_macro_use_imports()` function (lines 1074-1168) processes `#[macro_use]` attribute on extern crate declarations\n- `add_macro_use_binding()` function (lines 1061-1071) adds macros to the `macro_use_prelude` for all editions\n- The `contains_macro_use()` function (lines 1171-1189) identifies `#[macro_use]` attributes\n\n### Edition-Specific Prelude Collision Detection\n\n**compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/method/prelude_edition_lints.rs** handles edition-dependent method call collisions:\n\n- `lint_edition_dependent_dot_call()` (lines 20-234) detects when trait methods added to prelude in newer editions would become ambiguous\n- Lines 35-77: Maps method names to edition-specific lint types:\n  - `try_into` added in 2021 edition (line 37)\n  - `poll` and `into_future` added in 2024 edition (lines 39, 50)\n- `lint_fully_qualified_call_from_2018()` (lines 236-342) warns about trait-associated functions that became ambiguous in Rust 2021\n\n### Summary\n\nThe migration from Edition 2018 to 2021 involves three key areas:\n\n1. **Prelude Exports**: Edition 2021 adds `TryFrom`, `TryInto`, and `FromIterator` to the standard library prelude; Edition 2024 adds `Future` and `IntoFuture`.\n\n2. **Import Path Resolution**: The resolver implements `ModuleAndExternPrelude` as a virtual module to handle backward compatibility for 2015 edition macros used in 2018+ edition crates, while 2018+ crates use `ExternPrelude` directly for absolute paths.\n\n3. **Macro Variants**: Edition-specific panic macros (`panic_2015` vs `panic_2021`) change how string formatting is handled, with 2021 requiring explicit format_args for all complex cases.\n\nThe `macro_use` attribute works consistently across editions but interacts differently with scope resolution due to the `MacroUsePrelude` scope being treated specially in 2015 edition (line 160 of ident.rs)."
}

